<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../895/6992895.xml">
VJ</link></kind>
</category>
</concept>
</idea>
</genre>
 for the television show <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../260/200260.xml">
Total Request Live</link></series>
</it> on <channel wordnetid="106259898" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../856/18856.xml">
MTV</link></channel>
. She was supposed to be a guest commentator for one segment, but producers decided to offer her a permanent job. Burton had a small part on the TV series <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../096/166096.xml">
Dawson's Creek</link></series>
</it> , and this led to her role as <fictional_character wordnetid="109587565" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../729/2151729.xml">
Peyton Sawyer</link></fictional_character>
 on the series <it>One Tree Hill</it>. Burton appeared once on the television series <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../986/643986.xml">
Hey Dude</link></series>
</it>. She made her feature film debut in <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../175/10002175.xml">
Our Very Own</link></movie>
</it>, a comedy set in 1970s Nashville. Burton was featured on the cover of the Jan/Feb 2004 issue of <work wordnetid="104599396" confidence="0.8">
<product wordnetid="104007894" confidence="0.8">
<magazine wordnetid="106595351" confidence="0.8">
